You use Tinder to meet people, maybe.

83
00:06:18,509 --> 00:06:22,340
Maybe you use Tinder to find a girlfriend
or a boyfriend.

84
00:06:22,340 --> 00:06:24,680
Maybe you use Tinder to hook up with people.

85
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:29,330
So, again, this is giving the reason why you
do something.

86
00:06:29,330 --> 00:06:31,310
Why do you go to university?

87
00:06:31,310 --> 00:06:35,050
You go to university to learn.

88
00:06:35,050 --> 00:06:37,470
Why do you go to a restaurant?

89
00:06:37,470 --> 00:06:40,980
You go to a restaurant to eat good food.

90
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:44,700
So, these are just some more examples of the
infinitive.

91
00:06:44,700 --> 00:06:49,440
Now, let's learn about a way to use this in
a more formal sentence.

92
00:06:49,440 --> 00:06:53,560
So, sometimes we might want to make our English
more formal.

93
00:06:53,560 --> 00:06:59,080
So, we might want to do this if we're writing
an essay for university or if we're doing

94
00:06:59,080 --> 00:07:00,539
a presentation at work.

95
00:07:00,539 --> 00:07:04,430
So, more formal is when you use more serious
English.

96
00:07:04,430 --> 00:07:09,879
So, how can we explain a reason by using more
serious English?

97
00:07:09,879 --> 00:07:14,090
Well, we can use the expression "in order
to".

98
00:07:14,090 --> 00:07:18,510
It's similar to what we've just been doing,
but again, this is the more formal way.

99
00:07:18,510 --> 00:07:21,919
So, let's look at some examples.

100
00:07:21,919 --> 00:07:29,150
"People use EngVid in order to learn for free."

101
00:07:29,150 --> 00:07:35,270
So, if you look at this example, we still
have our infinitive verb.

102
00:07:35,270 --> 00:07:38,319
Can you tell me what the infinitive verb is
in this?

103
00:07:38,319 --> 00:07:40,530
"To learn", okay?

104
00:07:40,530 --> 00:07:47,639
So, we have our preposition "to" here and
then we have the base verb "learn".

105
00:07:47,639 --> 00:07:53,789
Before we have "to learn", we have the words
"in order", so this again is giving a reason.

106
00:07:53,789 --> 00:07:59,139
We could also say "People use EngVid to learn
for free" if we didn't want to use this, but

107
00:07:59,139 --> 00:08:04,159
to make it more formal we can add the words
"in order" before.

108
00:08:04,159 --> 00:08:07,070
What's another example of this?

109
00:08:07,070 --> 00:08:16,790
Maybe "People drink water in order to be less
thirsty.", okay?

110
00:08:16,790 --> 00:08:21,470
So, again, this is another example of using
"in order to".

111
00:08:21,470 --> 00:08:27,610
Now, if we want to say something in the negative,
okay, we want to prevent something, we can

112
00:08:27,610 --> 00:08:30,289
also use "in order not to".

113
00:08:30,289 --> 00:08:32,909
So, let's look an example of this.

114
00:08:32,909 --> 00:08:40,829
"I walked quietly in order not to wake you."

115
00:08:40,830 --> 00:08:45,420
So, the reason that I'm walking quietly, why
are you walking quietly?

116
00:08:45,420 --> 00:08:47,180
I don't want to wake you up.

117
00:08:47,180 --> 00:08:56,070
So, I've put that in the sentence: I walked
quietly in order not to wake you.

118
00:08:56,070 --> 00:09:02,470
So, in this case, it's almost similar to the
structure of this sentence, the only difference

119
00:09:02,470 --> 00:09:09,140
is we've added the word "not" here, because
we don't want to wake you up.

120
00:09:09,140 --> 00:09:13,460
What's the infinitive in this example?

121
00:09:13,460 --> 00:09:14,460
To wake.

122
00:09:14,460 --> 00:09:20,480
So again, we have our preposition and the
verb "wake".

123
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:26,590
Let's look at another example: "I stayed up"
I stayed up late, this was true when I was

124
00:09:26,590 --> 00:09:33,870
a child, "I stayed up late in order not to
miss Santa Claus."

125
00:09:33,870 --> 00:09:39,390
Okay, I was really scared of not seeing Santa
Claus when I was a kid, so I stayed up very

126
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:43,510
late in order not to miss Santa Claus.

127
00:09:43,510 --> 00:09:46,250
So, that's the reason I stayed up late.

128
